The start symbol is S → NT7 NT9, so any generated string must begin with a token that NT7 can ultimately produce as its first terminal.

Inspecting all terminal productions reachable from NT7:

• NT7 → 't21' | 't14' | 't33' | 't9' | 't11' | 't13' | 't15' | 't34'  
• NT7 → NT8 NT4   (first token comes from NT8)  
   – NT8 can only yield 't7', 't33', 't22', 't32', 't28', 't4', 't15', 't29'  
• NT7 → NT9 NT3   (first token comes from NT9)  
   – NT9 can only start with tokens derivable from NT7 or NT8, none of which include t20.

Thus, whatever derivation is followed, the first token produced by NT7 must be one of  
{ t7, t9, t11, t13, t14, t15, t21, t22, t28, t29, t32, t33, t34 }.

The given string starts with t20, which is not in this set, so no derivation from S can match the string.

Therefore the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

No

Only the non-terminal NT3 can produce the terminal token ‘t1’.  
In any derivation the first token of the generated string comes from the leftmost
non-terminal produced by the start symbol S.

S → NT7 NT9  
⟹ the first token must be produced by NT7.

Check whether NT7 can ever start with ‘t1’:

• NT7 has direct terminal productions for  
  t21, t14, t33, t9, t11, t15, t13, t34 – ‘t1’ is not among them.

• The two binary rules for NT7 are  
  NT7 → NT9 NT3 and NT7 → NT8 NT4.  
  In both cases the first token of the derived string comes from NT9 or NT8,
  respectively.

– NT8’s direct terminals are t7, t33, t22, t4, t15, t28, t32, t29 (no ‘t1’) and its only
  binary rule starts with NT9, so NT8 can never begin with ‘t1’.

– NT9’s direct terminals are t7, t22, t8, t32, t11, t13, t19, t24, t2, t26 (no ‘t1’).  
  Its binary rules begin with NT7 or NT9, neither of which can introduce ‘t1’
  (as just shown). Therefore NT9 can never begin with ‘t1’.

Since neither NT8 nor NT9 can start with ‘t1’, NT7 cannot start with ‘t1’, and consequently no string derived from S can start with ‘t1’.

The given string begins with ‘t1’, hence it is impossible for the grammar to generate it.
